'''Peter B. "Bo" Rutledge''' is the [[Dean (education)|Dean]] and the Herman E. Talmadge Chair of Law at the [[University of Georgia School of Law]] in Athens, Georgia.<ref>http://www.law.uga.edu/profile/peter-b-bo-rutledge</ref> An [[United States|American]] [[Lawyer|attorney]], [[academic]] and a specialist in [[Business transaction management|international business transactions]], [[dispute resolution|international dispute resolution]], [[litigation]], [[arbitration]], and the [[United States Supreme Court|U.S. Supreme Court]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://judiciary.house.gov/hearings/pdf/Rutledge071025.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100106114319/http://judiciary.house.gov/hearings/pdf/Rutledge071025.pdf |archivedate=2010-01-06 |df= }} October 25, 2007. U.S. House of Representatives Testimony to the House Judiciary Subcomittee on Commercial and Administrative Law on H.R. 3010, the "Arbitration Fairness Act of 2007".</ref><ref name=Bo>{{cite web|title=Peter B. "Bo" Rutledge|url=http://www.law.uga.edu/profile/peter-b-bo-rutledge|website=law.uga.edu|publisher=University of Georgia|accessdate=19 April 2017}}</ref> he served as a law clerk for [[Clarence Thomas|Associate U.S. Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas]] in 1998.<ref>http://law.uga.edu/sites/default/files/rutledgecv.pdf{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} CV</ref>
==Professional career== Rutledge received his undergraduate degree, ''[[magna cum laude]],'' from [[Harvard University]] and an M.Litt. in Applied Ethics from the [[University of Aberdeen]] (Scotland). He earned his J.D. degree with ''[[Latin honors|high honors]]''<!--is this a translation from Latin?--> from the [[University of Chicago School of Law]], where he served as [[Executive Editor]] of the [[University of Chicago Law Review]] and was inducted into the [[Order of the Coif]]. He clerked for renowned [[feeder judge]] [[United States Court of Appeals for the Fourth Circuit|Court of Appeals]] [[J. Harvie Wilkinson III|Judge J. Harvie Wilkinson III]] in 1997. After clerking with [[Clarence Thomas|Supreme Court Justice Thomas]], Rutledge practiced law as an associate [[Attorney at law|attorney]] at [[Freshfields Bruckhaus Deringer|Freshfields]] and [[Wilmer Cutler|WilmerHale]]. In 2008, he argued before the [[United States Supreme Court|Supreme Court]] in [[List of United States Supreme Court cases, volume 553|''Irrizary v. United States'']].<ref>{{SCOTUS URL Docket|06-7517}} Docket for 06-7517, ''Irrizary v. United States'', argued by Peter B. Rutledge as ''amicus curiae'' on April 15, 2008.</ref> He also joined the [[John McCain presidential campaign, 2008|John McCain's 2008 presidential campaign]] as a judicial advisory committee member.
==Teaching career== In 2003, Rutledge accepted a teaching position as an associate professor of law at the [[Columbus School of Law]] at The Catholic University of America, and was chosen as Professor of the Year for four consecutive years. In 2008, he accepted a position as a tenured associate professor of law at the [[University of Georgia School of Law]]. He served as the law school's Associate Dean for Faculty Development from 2013-2014, and became its Dean on January 1, 2015. Rutledge [[teacher|teaches]] [[Civil Procedure]], [[Business transaction management|International Business Transactions]] and [[Litigation|International Litigation]] and [[Arbitration]]. He has [[lecture|lectured]] at universities such as [[Oxford University]], [[Cambridge University]] as well as [[Fulbright Program|Fulbright Professor]] at the Institut für Zivilverfahrensrecht. Besides his [[Teacher|teaching]] and [[writing]], Rutledge is sought for [[legal advice]] and [[Expert|expertise]] on matters such as [[litigation]], [[arbitration]], the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] and [[dispute resolution|international dispute resolution]] including appearing as an [[expert witness]] in both [[litigation]] and [[arbitration]], and multiple times testifying before the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] on pending [[legislation]].<ref name=Bo />
==Examples of published works== Born, Gary and Peter B. Rutledge. (2006). ''International Civil Litigation in United States Courts''. [[Aspen Publishers]]. {{ISBN|0-7355-6307-1}}
Peter B. Rutledge. '(2012). ''Arbitration and the Constitution''. [[Cambridge University Press]]. {{ISBN|1107006112}}
Additionally, Rutledge has been published by the [[Oxford University Press]], the [[Yale University Press]] and the [[Cambridge University Press]], and has had articles appear in several journals and law reviews such as [[University of Chicago Law Review]], [[Vanderbilt Law Review]] and Journal of International Arbitration.<ref name=Bo />
